rName` typically works for existing classes with a constant string if the class is present. However, a dynamic tracker does record calls, which complicates things slightly. Maybe I could leverage Log4j 1 since HSQLDB first tries v2, then falls back to v1?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating interface methods**\\n\\nI’m reflecting on the configuration required for interface methods. It seems I need to ensure that dynamic access coverage addresses uncovered call sites. If the native setup is lacking reflect configuration, it could potentially lead to failures. It’s interesting how this all ties together, and I want to make sure I'm covering all the bases to avoid any issues! Overall, it's about ensuring robust access and functionality.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating log4j options**\\n\\nI’m considering the method signature and whether a provider is available, but it seems like there might not be coverage. I think V1 could work, especially since HSQLDB fits into that era. I need to gather native metadata for log4j V1 manually. Also, I can see that the test source can import org.apache.log4j.Logger with compile and testImplementation, so I may find a way to make use of that effectively.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_RDT0hF675vFp2PCO4w02wG4I|fc_0e3cab2072cbe6b80169f1703162b481939254da5af8eff4d0", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/log4j/log4j -name 'log4j-1.2.17.jar' | head -1 | xargs -r javap -classpath | head -20", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 293, "output": 1677, "cacheRead": 49664, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 51634, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777430549970, "responseId": "resp_0e3cab2072cbe6b80169f1701687408193b9cc6d9bcff5a743"}}
